        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>Mon cher M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Beke</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>Je vais faire des recherches à <hi rend="underline">tête reposée</hi> dans le Museum &amp; les Transactions pouvoir vous envoyer plus tard des renseignements plus précis—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>T à vs | L. Bouton <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> 24 Sep</p>
<p>Extrait d’une lettre de M Autard de Bragard— Savane—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> 17 Sept— 1856</p>
<p>En 1835—36—ou 37, j’ai envoyé à la Société d’histoire naturelle un Merle huppé de Bourbon<ref target="#foot.f5"/> “Turdus cafer” pris au Morne Brabant peu de temps après un coup de vent— aussi un autre oiseau tué à la Savane reconnu appartenir à une espèce de Madagascar—</p>
<p>Vous trouverez ces individus au Museum et ce qui les concerne inséré dans les transactions de la Société—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note><hi rend="italic">Top of first page</hi>: ‘Case of Madagascan Bird blown to Mauritius &amp; one from Bourbon.—’ <hi rend="italic">pencil</hi>; ‘19’<ref target="#foot.f6"/> <hi rend="italic">brown crayon</hi></note>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="translation">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Beke</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                    <p>I shall do some research at leisure in the Museum &amp; and in the Transactions on the subject referred to in order to be able to send you later more precise details—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
                    <p>Ever yours | L. Bouton <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
                    <p>24 Sep</p>
<p>Extract from a letter of M Autard de Bragard— Savanne—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> 17 Sept— 1856</p>
                    <p>In 1835—36—or 37, I sent to the Natural History Society a crested thrush from Bourbon<ref target="#foot.f5"/>   “Turdus cafer” taken at Morne Brabant a short time after a hurricane— Also another bird killed in the Savanne known to belong to a Madagascan species—</p>
<p>You will find these specimens in the Museum and details concerning them in the transactions of the Society—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">For a translation of this letter, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 6, Appendix I.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot_trans.f1">For the transcription of this letter in its original French and for CD’s annotations, see p. 232.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The year is given by the extract included in the letter.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1956.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Victor de Robillard, 20 September 1856</ref>, in which it is mentioned that <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_370.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Tilstone Beke</ref> had communicated a request from CD to the Société d’Histoire Naturelle of Mauritius. Bouton was secretary of the society until his death in 1878.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Savanne is a district of south-west Mauritius.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Bourbon was the former name of Réunion Island, 130 miles south-west of Mauritius. The bird was possibly the now extinct Réunion huppe (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2059.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Victor de Robillard, 26 February 1857</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">The number of CD’s portfolio of notes on the geographical distribution of animals.</note>
        </div>        
            
